doc.title: Market Insights GSLatAm Daily 09.02: NEXT25, RDOR3, LatAm Telco

passages.text: BZ Supreme Court begins the first day of trial of former President Jair Bolsonaro over charges of an attempted coup after his 2022 election defeat to President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva. Trial starts today and has more sessions scheduled over the next 10 days (BBG). Meanwhile, CNN Brasil reported that US govt is considering measures against Banco do Brasil bank and Brazil's diesel imports from Russia, and it would be implemented within a week or a week and a half.

In Mexico, headline inflation expectations for 2025/26 improved slightly in the latest central bank monthly survey. Workers' remittances firmed slightly in July: US \(5.33bn (- 4.7\%\) yoy; \(+1.6\%\) mom sa), slightly above consensus. For Chile, the Chilean banking regulator released system data for July, showing loan growth acceleration and stable asset quality trends for the system and BCI.
From GS GIR. Any references to we/us/our refers to research' views.

FNEXT - Initiate at Buy: Our P \(123 PT implies 23\%\) upside while our 2026 dividend expectation implies a \(7\%\) dividend yield. The newest Fibra will quickly become one of the largest industrial companies in Mexico, making it the second largest pure play REIT after F. Prologis... While an initially complicated story to understand given the different types of consolidation taking place, we believe that the key consideration is that Fibra Next provides investors with exposure to the fastest growing industrial real estate markets by industry focus (logistics, \(80\%\) of tenants) and region (Mexico City, \(55\%\) of revenues). Despite its name, NEXT is more focused on non- nearshoring impacted markets, a positive amid trade policy uncertainty. We see three demand drivers for Fibra Next:

Mark to market for the 7.4 mm sqm stabilized portfolio which could lead to \(20\%\) lease spreads in the near term; 2. Access to a 6 mm sqm landbank, 2/3 of which is in Mexico City, with a target yield on costs of \(10\%\) 3. Possible increase in liquidity following recent shareholder transactions which will allow for the contribution of the Fibra Uno portfolio (6.1 mm sqm) and additional Jupiter portfolios (757k sqm), pending the approval of the Anti- trust vote (discussed below).

Exhibit 3: The Next stabilized portfolio will be the second biggest among peers, yet with most exposure to the Center of Sao Paulo...  Mexico Industrial Real Estate Coverage Universe - Regional Breakdown (000s sqm)

RDOR: Co signed an agreement with Atlántica Hospitais to contribute its Hospital Glória D' Or, located in Rio de Janeiro, to the Atlantica D'Or joint venture. Recall that Rede D'Or holds a controlling stake of \(50.01\%\) in Atlantica D'Or, also serving as the hospital operator, while the remaining \(49.99\%\) is held by Atlântica Hospitais, indirectly owned by Bradesco Seguros. We read the announcement as another move that underscores the strengthening of the commercial relationship between Rede D'Or and Bradesco Saude, which we welcome for RDOR's equity story given Bradesco's solid footprint in the health beneficiaries market in Brazil. All in, the deal corroborates our view that the JV will indeed become a key expansion vehicle for RDOR's hospital business, but we await more visibility on whether it could be used for other mature assets. We remain Buy- rated on RDOR3 with a TP of BRL 45.

LatAm Telco: In this note we analyze Brazil telecom- market data for July (as recently released by regulator Anatel) where we highlight mainly: 1) stronger postpaid volumes by VIV and TIMB (compared to June), 2) AMX accelerating the increase in fiber- broadband subscribers (which reached \(\sim 22\%\) of its fixed- broadband base, with faster fiber growth accompanied by higher cable disconnections, potentially reflecting technology upgrades).
(- )BBAS3 BZ: US Govt is preparing sanctions against Banco do Brasil in the context of the beginning the trial of Bolsonaro.
(+) SAPR11 BZ: Company received a net amount of R\$4bn regarding a court- ordered payment related to a suit filed against the Union.

\*Desk ended the last trading session as a Net SELLER in R\$0.625mln. We were net buyers of STBP3, COGN3, BEEF3, RAIL3, GGBR; net sellers of CSAN3, B3SA3, ABEV3, RADL3, EQTl3, GMAT3; and both ways on SRNA3, CSAN3, RDOR3.
\* Brazil Aug Manufacturing PMI due 10ANZBT / 9 AM EST \* Brazil 2Q25 GDP due 9AM BZT / 8 AM EST
Last week B3 registered a small inflow from Foreigners of around US\(31mln. YTD Brazil is still registering an inflow of US\)3.58bln. See flows monitor here
What happened in Brazil in May: Brazil continues to be one of the Top Emerging Market Performers YTD (EEM +8.85% vs EWZ +20.88%), only behind Mexico, Chile and South Africa. See the full recap here

Brazil Positioning: Ibovespa made all- time highs in local currency terms but still \(40\%\) away from USD ATH from over 10 yrs ago. All of this price action was driven by foreign accounts adding Brazil - over the last month alone Foreign Investors have add US\(3.3 - over the same time period Ibov moved 7% higher. so for every +US\)1bn of foreign inflow index moved by \(\sim 2.15\%\) . Locals were sellers, and data shows that \(0\%\) of market cap shorted has INCREASED despite the move higher. See full positioning

BZ Utilities - We update our estimates for Brazilian utilities Eletrobras and Copel to take into account 2Q25 earnings results (ELET / CPLE) and Eletrobras's BRL 4bn interim dividends announcement. We now expect Eletrobras DY to reach \(8\% /12\%\) in 2025/26E and avg \(\sim 20\%\) over 2027- 30 (in our base case scenario) backed by the company's capital allocation methodology guidelines (for which the company provided more color on today's earnings call). here.

Petrobras (PBR): For illustrative purposes, we benchmark Petrobras' key operational and valuation metrics against those of global oil majors and try to assess potential room for efficiency gains. Overall, our analysis suggests up to \(28\%\) upside potential to the current share price if we were to assume potential OPEX reductions are implemented, as well as some CAPEX rationalization. Moreover, should Petrobras re- rate to the average FCFy of global oil majors, there could be up to an additional \(13\%\) upside potential for reference. See the full note here

Brazil Healthcare - Health- plan sector: In June 2025, sector net adds were up by 261k MoM (reaching \(+432k\) YTD). On a YoY basis, sector membership base is up by \(2.7\%\) YoY, as we see churn decrease leading to a timid but consistent growth despite flat gross adds. See the full note here

Within LatAm Financials: Mexican banks sold off post Mexico elections on the back of fears of limiting tax benefits or potential cap to rates (link) but so far, there are no indications that this is something the government is targeting. Financials was the worst performing sector since the event, and we see investors willing to pick up the space from here, as soon as we see some stability on FX volatility. From convos with US investors, we see ITUB as the most crowded name in fins, followed by GFNORTOE and NU. BBDC and DLO remain the lightest at the bottom of the list - see full positioning score here LatAm Fins: US marketing feedback

LatAm Weekly Wrap: LatAm politics and markets are hard to disentangle. As election calendars heat up across the region, the volume of headlines—and noise—continues to build up... See LatAm Weekly Wrap Here
